Australian Government to Invest AU$1 Billion in ""Pit-to-Panel""
Strategy

Apr. 03, 2024 10:00AM PST

Share

Giann Liguid

In what it's calling a pit-to-panel strategy, Australia is looking to boost its solar panel
manufacturing capabilities with the Solar Sunshot program.

ME Image / Shutterstock

Australia has announced a AU$1 billion investment in the Solar Sunshot program,
which is aimed at bolstering the country's solar panel manufacturing sector and
realizing its potential as a renewable energy powerhouse.

GOLD PRICE

SILVER PRICE

COPPER PRICE OIL PRICE URANIUM ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE

The Solar Sunshot program is seeking to revamp Australia's solar panel manufacturing
industry by facilitating a transition from extracting and exporting materials to full scale

industry by facilitating a transition from extracting and exporting materials to full-scale
solar panel production, a strategy it has dubbed “pit to panel.”

With abundant reserves of metals and minerals like aluminium, phosphate, silica-bearing
quartz and copper, Australia is looking to establish a robust domestic supply chain for solar
panels.

“Historically, Australia has been good at going from the mining pit to port, and long may
this continue. But the Australian Government will also invest in the path from pit to panels
and capture more value for our economy and workforce,” said Australian Prime Minister
Anthony Albanese in a March 28 press release.

The initiative comes as the nation grapples with economic shifts following the closure of
coal-␀red power stations.

By investing in strategic manufacturing capabilities and promoting innovation, the
government wants to create a competitive solar panel manufacturing industry that
contributes to job creation and regional development.

